  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>Why Add a Battery?</h2>
      <p>
        Solar panels generate electricity during the day, but most households use the bulk of their energy in the evening. Without storage, that daytime solar is exported to the grid for a fraction of what you pay to buy it back at night.
      </p>
      <p>
        A home battery stores your excess solar generation and releases it when you need it — after dark, during peak tariff periods, or during a grid outage. The result is <strong>less energy purchased from the grid</strong> and more value from every panel on your roof.
      </p>

      <h2>How It Works</h2>
      <p>
        Your solar panels charge the battery during the day. When the battery is full, any remaining excess is exported to the grid. In the evening, your home draws from the battery first, only pulling from the grid once the battery is depleted.
      </p>
      <p>
        Modern battery systems are managed by a built-in battery management system (BMS) that handles charge cycles, temperature, and cell balancing automatically. You monitor everything from an app on your phone.
      </p>

      <h2>What Size Battery Do You Need?</h2>
      <p>
        The right battery size depends on your household energy profile — how much solar you generate, when you use energy, and what you want the battery to cover.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>5 kWh</strong> — suits smaller households or those wanting to offset evening peak usage</li>
        <li><strong>10 kWh</strong> — covers most of the overnight consumption for an average home</li>
        <li><strong>13–15 kWh</strong> — for larger homes or those aiming for near grid independence</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        We design every system around your actual energy data — not a one-size-fits-all estimate. During your consultation, we'll review your bills, usage patterns, and solar generation to recommend the right capacity.
      </p>

      <h2>Victorian Battery Rebate</h2>
      <p>
        The Victorian Government offers a rebate on home battery installations through the Solar Victoria program. Eligibility depends on your property type, household income, and whether you already have solar installed.
      </p>
      <p>
        As a Solar Victoria approved retailer, we handle the rebate application as part of your installation — you don't need to apply separately.
      </p>
      <p>
        Additional federal incentives through Small-scale Technology Certificates (STCs) also reduce the upfront cost of qualifying systems.
      </p>

      <h2>What Affects the Cost?</h2>
      <p>
        Battery pricing depends on several factors:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Capacity</strong> — larger batteries cost more but store more energy</li>
        <li><strong>Chemistry</strong> — lithium iron phosphate (LiFePO4) costs more upfront but lasts longer and is safer than other lithium chemistries</li>
        <li><strong>Hybrid vs retrofit</strong> — installing a battery alongside a new solar system is typically more cost-effective than retrofitting an existing system</li>
        <li><strong>Backup capability</strong> — full home backup during outages requires additional switchgear</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        We provide a detailed, itemised quote after your consultation — no hidden costs or vague estimates.
      </p>

      <h2>Battery Backup and Off-Grid</h2>
      <p>
        A standard grid-connected battery will not power your home during a blackout unless it's configured for backup. We offer full backup solutions that keep your essential circuits running when the grid goes down.
      </p>
      <p>
        For properties suited to it, we also design off-grid and hybrid systems that can operate independently of the grid entirely. Our <a href="/laboratory/environmental-service-pod">Environmental Service Pod</a> integrates battery storage with solar, heat pump, and heating/cooling in a single modular system designed for grid independence.
      </p>

